∈ C|Ω|×s (Matrix representing a signal)</strong>: This represents a matrix X that contains signals from the domain Ω. The matrix has dimensions related to the size of Ω and another parameter s.</p></li><li><p><strong>xu ∈ Cs (Vector representing a signal)</strong>: This is a vector representation of a signal at a specific point u in the domain Ω.</p></li><li><p><strong>xuj ∈ C (Component of a signal)</strong>: Represents a specific component (jth component) of the signal at point u.</p></li><li><p><strong>F(X) (Function on signals)</strong>: A function that operates on discrete domain signals X and returns another discrete domain signal.</p></li><li><p><strong>τ : Ω → Ω (Automorphism of the domain)</strong>: An automorphism is a transformation of a set that preserves its structure. Here, τ is a function that maps the domain Ω onto itself in a structure-preserving way.</p></li><li><p><strong>η : Ω → Ω0 (Isomorphism between domains)</strong>: An isomorphism is a structure-preserving mapping between two different domains (Ω and Ω0 in this case).</p></li><li><p><strong>σ : C → C0 (Activation function)</strong>: In the context of neural networks, this is a function that introduces non-linearity (like the ReLU or sigmoid functions).</p></li><li><p><strong>G = (V,E) (Graph)</strong>: A graph G consisting of a set of nodes V and a set of edges E connecting these nodes.</p></li><li><p><strong>T = (V,E,F) (Mesh)</strong>: A mesh T with nodes V, edges E, and faces F. This is often used in 3D modeling and computer graphics.</p></li><li><p><strong>x ? θ (Convolution with filter θ)</strong>: This represents the convolution operation with a filter θ, a fundamental operation in signal processing and neural networks.</p></li><li><p><strong>Sv (Shift operator)</strong>: This is an operator that shifts a function or a signal.</p></li><li><p><strong>ϕi (Basis function)</strong>: Basis functions are the building blocks for constructing other functions, often used in areas like Fourier series.</p></li><li><p><strong>TuΩ, TΩ (Tangent space, tangent bundle)</strong>: TuΩ is the tangent space at a point u in Ω, which is a concept from differential geometry. TΩ is the tangent bundle, which is the collection of all tangent spaces at all points in Ω.</p></li><li><p><strong>X ∈ TuΩ (Tangent vector)</strong>: This represents a tangent vector in the tangent space at point u.</p></li><li><p><strong>gu(X,Y ) = hX,Y iu (Riemannian metric)</strong>: A Riemannian metric is a way of measuring distances and angles on a curved surface. gu is such a metric, and hX,Y iu represents the inner product of vectors X and Y in the metric space at point u.</p></li><li><p><strong>‘(γ), ‘uv (Length of a curve, discrete metric)</strong>: ‘(γ) refers to the length of a curve γ, while ‘uv is a discrete metric measuring distances between points u and v, typically in a graph or network.</p></li></ol><p>These notations are foundational to understanding the mathematical concepts in geometric deep learning, providing the tools to describe complex data structures and transformations.</p></div></div></div><div class="mt-1 flex justify-start gap-3 empty:hidden"><div class="text-gray-400 flex self-end lg:self-center justify-center lg:justify-start mt-0 -ml-1 visible"><span class="" data-state="closed"><button class="flex items-center gap-1.5 rounded-md p-1 text-xs text-token-text-tertiary hover:text-token-text-primary md:invisible md:group-hover:visible md:group-[.final-completion]:visible"><svg width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="icon-md"><path fill-rule="evenodd" clip-rule="evenodd" d="M12 4C10.8954 4 10 4.89543 10 6H14C14 4.89543 13.1046 4 12 4ZM8.53513 4C9.22675 2.8044 10.5194 2 12 2C13.4806 2 14.7733 2.8044 15.4649 4H17C18.6569 4 20 5.34315 20 7V19C20 20.6569 18.6569 22 17 22H7C5.34315 22 4 20.6569 4 19V7C4 5.34315 5.34315 4 7 4H8.53513ZM8 6H7C6.44772 6 6 6.44772 6 7V19C6 19.5523 6.44772 20 7 20H17C17.5523 20 18 19.5523 18 