s or complex systems) can be difficult, most real-world tasks are not random but have underlying patterns or regularities. These patterns are often linked to the lower-dimensional structure of the physical world.</p></li><li><p><strong>Geometric Principles in Deep Learning</strong>: The authors want to reveal these regularities using geometric principles. They note that exploiting known symmetries (like how objects behave under rotation or movement) can help manage the complexity of high-dimensional data.</p></li><li><p><strong>Examples of Geometric Regularity</strong>: The paper will explore various models, including Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs), Recurrent Neural Networks (RNNs), Graph Neural Networks (GNNs), and Transformers, and show how they are connected by geometric principles.</p></li><li><p><strong>Scope and Focus</strong>: The authors clarify that their focus is on learning architectures and the symmetries in data. They won't delve deeply into other aspects of neural network applications like self-supervised learning or generative modeling, nor will they focus on optimization techniques like Adam or dropout.</p></li><li><p><strong>Significance and Application</strong>: The principles discussed are believed to be important across various deep learning areas, even if those specific areas aren't the main focus of this work.</p></li><li><p><strong>Purpose and Limitation</strong>: The goal is to provide a broad view of the power of geometric principles in deep learning, but not to cover all research in this area. The authors aim to demonstrate these principles through well-known architectures and hope to provide enough references for readers to apply these principles in future work.</p></li></ol></div></div></div><div class="mt-1 flex justify-start gap-3 empty:hidden"><div class="text-gray-400 flex self-end lg:self-center justify-center lg:justify-start mt-0 -ml-1 visible"><span class="" data-state="closed"><button class="flex items-center gap-1.5 rounde