ful Applications</strong>: By the time the text was written, GNNs had shown significant success in molecular property prediction, including in areas like virtual screening for new drugs.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Node Embeddings</strong>:</p><ul><li><strong>Early Success in Deep Learning on Graphs</strong>: One of the earliest successes of deep learning in graphs involved learning node representations in an unsupervised manner, based on the graph's structure.</li><li><strong>Random Walk-Based Embeddings</strong>: Techniques like DeepWalk, node2vec, and LINE used random walks to learn node representations, clustering nodes that co-occur in these walks. Planetoid was the first to incorporate label information in this approach.</li><li><strong>Unifying Random Walks with GNN Encoders</strong>: Attempts to combine random walk-based objectives with GNNs led to mixed results. It was found that GNNs intrinsically push neighboring node representations together, a discovery that shifted focus away from random walk objectives towards contrastive approaches.</li><li><strong>New Directions</strong>: This shift led to the development of methods like Deep Graph Informax (DGI), GRACE, and BERT-like objectives, which were inspired by mutual information maximization and techniques successful in image domain analysis.</li></ul></li></ol><p>Overall, the section highlights the diverse origins and developments of GNNs, showing how they have evolved from specific applications in computational chemistry to more general methods in machine learning, including the innovative approach of node embeddings.</p></div></div></div><div class="mt-1 flex justify-start gap-3 empty:hidden"><div class="text-gray-400 flex self-end lg:self-center justify-center lg:justify-start mt-0 -ml-1 visible"><span class="" data-state="closed"><button class="flex items-center gap-1.5 rounded-md p-1 text-xs text-token-text-tertiary hover:text-token-text-primary md:invisible md:group-hover:visible md:group-[.final-co