ith models like structure2vec. This model positioned graph representation learning as a Markov random field.</li><li><strong>Aligning Computations</strong>: The computations in mean-field inference and loopy belief propagation were aligned with the structure of GNNs, showing how these methods could work together.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Key Concept - Hilbert-Space Embeddings</strong>:</p><ul><li><strong>Embedding Probability Distributions</strong>: A crucial idea was using Hilbert-space embeddings of distributions. This involves embedding the probability distribution of node features into a space where each point represents a probability distribution.</li><li><strong>GNN Computations and Probability Distributions</strong>: This concept allows the representations computed by GNNs to correspond to embeddings of some probability distribution over the node features.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Innovative GNN Architectures</strong>:</p><ul><li><strong>Incorporating PGM Computations</strong>: New GNN architectures were inspired that more directly incorporate computations found in PGMs. Examples include combining GNNs with conditional random fields, relational Markov networks, and Markov logic networks.</li></ul></li></ol><p>In essence, the section highlights how the principles and techniques from probabilistic graphical models have been integrated into the development of Graph Neural Networks, leading to innovative architectures that leverage the strengths of both approaches. This integration allows GNNs to handle complex graph-structured data more effectively by incorporating probabilistic reasoning and inference mechanisms.</p></div></div></div><div class="mt-1 flex justify-start gap-3 empty:hidden"><div class="text-gray-400 flex self-end lg:self-center justify-center lg:justify-start mt-0 -ml-1 visible"><span class="" data-state="closed"><button class="flex items-center gap-1.5 rounded-md p-1 text-xs text-token-text-tertiary hover:text-token-text-primary md:invis