power of GNNs is closely tied to the WL test. GNNs conforming to specific structures cannot be more powerful than the WL test in distinguishing non-isomorphic graphs.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Injective Aggregation Functions</strong>:</p><ul><li><strong>Necessity for Maximally Expressive GNNs</strong>: For a GNN to match the representational power of the WL test, its aggregation function needs to be injective (uniquely mapping inputs to outputs). Summation is an example of such an injective function.</li><li><strong>Graph Isomorphism Network (GIN)</strong>: Xu et al. proposed the GIN as a maximally-expressive GNN under this framework, using an injective aggregation function.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Continuous Node Feature Spaces</strong>:</p><ul><li><strong>Challenges in Injectivity</strong>: The findings related to the WL test and GNNs do not directly apply to continuous node feature spaces, where achieving injective aggregation is more complex.</li><li><strong>Principal Neighbourhood Aggregation (PNA)</strong>: This approach proposes a multiple-aggregator GNN that has shown to be empirically powerful and stable in continuous feature spaces.</li></ul></li></ol><p>In summary, the Weisfeiler-Lehman formalism provides a framework for understanding the limitations and capabilities of GNNs in distinguishing graph structures. While GNNs are powerful, their ability to differentiate non-isomorphic graphs is inherently linked to the properties of their aggregation functions and the nature of the node features they process.</p></div></div></div><div class="mt-1 flex justify-start gap-3 empty:hidden"><div class="text-gray-400 flex self-end lg:self-center justify-center lg:justify-start mt-0 -ml-1 visible"><span class="" data-state="closed"><button class="flex items-center gap-1.5 rounded-md p-1 text-xs text-token-text-tertiary hover:text-token-text-primary md:invisible md:group-hover:visible md:group-[.final-completion]:visible"><svg width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 