s. These have been translated into more powerful k-GNN architectures.</li><li><strong>Scaling Challenges</strong>: While more powerful, these k-GNNs face practical scaling issues, particularly beyond k = 3.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Invariant and Equivariant Graph Networks</strong>:</p><ul><li><strong>Maron et al.'s Work</strong>: They studied invariant and equivariant graph networks over k-tuples of nodes and proposed scalable variants of these networks with the expressive power equivalent to the 3-WL test.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Augmenting GNN Inputs</strong>:</p><ul><li><strong>Identifying Features</strong>: Attaching identifying features to nodes can help GNNs detect specific structures. Proposals include using one-hot representations and random features.</li><li><strong>Incorporating Structural Information</strong>: Efforts have been made to incorporate structural information into the message-passing process of GNNs. This includes modulating the message function or the graph structure itself.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Interesting Approaches in Message Passing</strong>:</p><ul><li><strong>Anchor Node Sets, Laplacian Eigenvectors</strong>: Some methods involve sampling anchor node sets or aggregating based on Laplacian eigenvectors.</li><li><strong>Topological Data Analysis</strong>: Others use topological data analysis for positional embeddings or to drive the message-passing process.</li></ul></li></ol><p>In summary, while standard GNNs are powerful, there's ongoing research to enhance their ability to detect and represent complex structures in graphs. This includes developing higher-order methods and augmenting GNNs with additional features or structural information to overcome their inherent limitations.</p></div></div></div><div class="mt-1 flex justify-start gap-3 empty:hidden"><div class="text-gray-400 flex self-end lg:self-center justify-center lg:justify-start mt-0 -ml-1 visible"><span class="" data-state="closed"><button class="flex items-ce