ith multiscale wavelet decompositions, demonstrating the stability of these models against deformations and emphasizing the role of architectural depth.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Signal Processing on Graphs and Meshes</strong>:</p><ul><li><strong>Spectral GNNs</strong>: A class of GNNs known as spectral GNNs emerged from work in signal processing and computational harmonic analysis. They use the concept of the Graph Fourier Transform.</li><li><strong>Graph Signal Processing (GSP)</strong>: Influential work by Pierre Vandergheynst and José Moura popularized GSP, which generalizes Fourier transforms based on graph adjacency and Laplacian matrices.</li><li><strong>Spectral Graph Convolutional Networks</strong>: These networks, relying on spectral filters, have been highly influential in the field of machine learning on graphs. Notable works include those by Defferrard et al. and Kipf and Welling.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Non-Euclidean Harmonic Analysis in Computer Graphics</strong>:</p><ul><li><strong>Spectral Filters on Manifolds and Meshes</strong>: The use of spectral filters on manifolds and meshes predates GSP and has been influential in computer graphics.</li><li><strong>Applications in Shape Descriptors and Functional Maps</strong>: Spectral methods have been widely used in computer graphics for applications like shape descriptors and functional maps.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Learnable Shape Descriptors</strong>:</p><ul><li><strong>Similar to Spectral GNNs</strong>: Learnable shape descriptors similar to spectral GNNs were proposed by Roee Litman and Alex Bronstein.</li></ul></li></ol><p>In summary, the development of CNNs and GNNs has been significantly influenced by techniques from signal processing and harmonic analysis, demonstrating a rich interplay between computational neuroscience, image processing, and graph theory. These insights have led to more effective and theoretically grounded models in both machine learning and computer graphics.</p><