d postconditions.</li><li><strong>Preserving Algorithmic Invariants</strong>: The field of algorithmic reasoning focuses on designing neural networks that preserve these algorithmic invariants.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>General-Purpose Neural Computers</strong>:</p><ul><li><strong>Complex Architectures</strong>: Examples include the neural Turing machine and the differentiable neural computer. These architectures embody general computation but are often complex and challenging to optimize.</li><li><strong>Simple Relational Reasoners</strong>: In practice, simpler models like those proposed by Santoro et al. have shown to be more effective.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Focus on Primitive Algorithms</strong>:</p><ul><li><strong>Modelling Complex Postconditions</strong>: As it's challenging to model complex postconditions, much work has focused on learning to execute simple algorithms, such as basic arithmetic.</li><li><strong>Examples of Neural Models</strong>: This includes models like the neural GPU, neural RAM, neural programmer-interpreters, neural arithmetic-logic units, and neural execution engines.</li></ul></li></ol><p>In summary, algorithmic reasoning in neural networks represents a shift from spatially induced geometries to computational settings, where the focus is on mimicking algorithmic processes and preserving their inherent invariances. This area explores both complex general-purpose architectures and simpler models focused on specific algorithmic tasks.</p></div></div></div><div class="mt-1 flex justify-start gap-3 empty:hidden"><div class="text-gray-400 flex self-end lg:self-center justify-center lg:justify-start mt-0 -ml-1 visible"><span class="" data-state="closed"><button class="flex items-center gap-1.5 rounded-md p-1 text-xs text-token-text-tertiary hover:text-token-text-primary md:invisible md:group-hover:visible md:group-[.final-completion]:visible"><svg width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/sv