><li><strong>Physics Simulations</strong>: Significant progress has been made in using GNNs for physics simulations, which has also influenced the design of generalizing GNNs.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Preserving Invariants in Algorithms and Simulations</strong>:</p><ul><li><strong>Similar Requirements</strong>: Since algorithms can be phrased as discrete-time simulations (and vice versa), both require preserving similar invariants.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Challenges in Extrapolation</strong>:</p><ul><li><strong>Generalization Beyond Training Data</strong>: A major challenge for neural networks, including GNNs, is extrapolation - generalizing to data that differs significantly from the training set, such as in size or generative distribution.</li><li><strong>Geometric and Causal Approaches</strong>: To achieve effective extrapolation, the architecture and features of GNNs need to be designed to learn linear target functions. Causal reasoning approaches have also been proposed to yield environment-invariant graph representations.</li></ul></li></ol><p>In summary, this section highlights the advancements in using GNNs to model and solve complex algorithms and their potential in areas like reinforcement learning and physics. It also addresses the challenge of extrapolation in neural networks, emphasizing the need for careful design to ensure that GNNs can generalize well beyond the scenarios covered in their training data.</p></div></div></div><div class="mt-1 flex justify-start gap-3 empty:hidden"><div class="text-gray-400 flex self-end lg:self-center justify-center lg:justify-start mt-0 -ml-1 visible"><span class="" data-state="closed"><button class="flex items-center gap-1.5 rounded-md p-1 text-xs text-token-text-tertiary hover:text-token-text-primary md:invisible md:group-hover:visible md:group-[.final-completion]:visible"><svg width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="icon-md"><path fill-rule="evenodd"