g>Okapi Information Retrieval System</strong>:</p><ul><li><strong>Origin of the Name</strong>: The fuller name "Okapi BM25" comes from the first system that used this ranking function – the Okapi information retrieval system. This system was implemented at City University in London during the 1980s and 1990s.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Functionality Similar to TF-IDF</strong>:</p><ul><li><strong>TF-IDF-like Functions</strong>: BM25 and its variants (like BM25F) are similar to TF-IDF (Term Frequency-Inverse Document Frequency) in their operation. They are used in document retrieval, adjusting the importance (weight) of terms in a document based on their frequency.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Variants of BM25</strong>:</p><ul><li><strong>BM25F</strong>: This is a variant of BM25 that considers document structure and anchor text, offering a more nuanced approach to document ranking based on query relevance.</li></ul></li></ol><p>In summary, Okapi BM25 is a well-established ranking function in the realm of search engines and document retrieval, allowing for the effective ranking of documents based on query relevance, drawing on principles from the probabilistic retrieval framework.</p></div></div></div><div class="mt-1 flex justify-start gap-3 empty:hidden"><div class="text-gray-400 flex self-end lg:self-center justify-center lg:justify-start mt-0 -ml-1 visible"><span class="" data-state="closed"><button class="flex items-center gap-1.5 rounded-md p-1 text-xs text-token-text-tertiary hover:text-token-text-primary md:invisible md:group-hover:visible md:group-[.final-completion]:visible"><svg width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="icon-md"><path fill-rule="evenodd" clip-rule="evenodd" d="M12 4C10.8954 4 10 4.89543 10 6H14C14 4.89543 13.1046 4 12 4ZM8.53513 4C9.22675 2.8044 10.5194 2 12 2C13.4806 2 14.7733 2.8044 15.4649 4H17C18.6569 4 20 5.34315 20 7V19C20 20.6569 18.6569 22 17 22H7C5.34315 22 4 20.6569 4 19V7C4